I"5<p>Sitemaps are still important for SEO, perhaps one of the most improtant things.</p>

<p>An XML Sitemap is now really easy to setup in Jekyll - easier than Wordpress, even. Here is my <a href="/sitemap.xml">Sitemap</a>.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Simply add <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gem 'jekyll-sitemap'</code> to your GemFile* and then run <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bundle</code>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Add the following to your siteâ€™s _config.yml:</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<div class="language-yaml highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="na">gems</span><span class="pi">:</span>
  <span class="pi">-</span> <span class="s">jekyll-sitemap</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Serve your site with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bundle exec jekyll serve</code> and the sitemap should now be accessible at /sitemap.xml. (Set the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">url</code> parameter in _config.yml to configure the URL used in your sitemap.xml file).</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Set this as your Sitemap in <a href="https://www.google.com/webmasters/">Google Search Console</a> to reap the large SEO benefits.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>A massive thanks to the brilliant creators of the plugin used above: <a href="https://github.com/jekyll/jekyll-sitemap">Jekyll Sitemap</a>.</p>

<p><em>*(If you do not have a GemFile, create one looking something like <a href="https://github.com/samdoidge/samdoidge.com/blob/master/GemFile">mine</a>.)</em></p>
:ET